# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 16th-street-mall
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:16th-street-mall/131-ponce-de-leon-avenue] Pei's first project, built in 1949, a 50,000-square-foot (4,600 m2) two-story "box that invoked the lean rectilinearity of Mies van der Rohe".
[src:16th-street-mall/131-ponce-de-leon-avenue] The mixed-use development incorporates the entire block bounded by Ponce de Leon Avenue, North Avenue, Piedmont Avenue and Juniper Street, except for St.
[src:16th-street-mall/131-ponce-de-leon-avenue] A joint venture between real estate investment company Sereo Group Inc. and developer Faison Enterprises bought the 2.5-acre (10,000 m2) site in 2012.
[src:16th-street-mall/131-ponce-de-leon-avenue] In 2008, the block had been proposed for redevelopment as the "Fountain on Ponce" complex, but that project did not go through.
[src:16th-street-mall/131-ponce-de-leon-avenue] The building was demolished in February 2013, but the Atlanta Preservation Center stated that its understanding that a portion of the façade was to be "resurrected as a shell" and incorporated into the new complex.
[src:16th-street-mall/131-ponce-de-leon-avenue] The demolition involved taking apart the building piece by piece.
[src:16th-street-mall/131-ponce-de-leon-avenue] The front portion of the building was then reconstructed for use as the clubhouse and offices of the mixed use development.
[src:16th-street-mall/16th-street-mall] For Denver, 16th Street has long been an important commercial street.
[src:16th-street-mall/16th-street-mall] In the 1960s it was lined with movie theaters, department stores, banks, and retail outlets.
[src:16th-street-mall/16th-street-mall] However, by the 1970s, downtown Denver faced severe bus congestion on 16th and 17th streets, more than 600 daily trips, contributing to air pollution and traffic congestion.
[src:16th-street-mall/16th-street-mall] The area's design also discouraged pedestrian activity.
[src:16th-street-mall/16th-street-mall] To address these issues, the downtown business community and the Regional Transportation District (RTD) proposed building bus transfer stations at Market Street and Broadway, connected by a pedestrian mall with a free shuttle bus service.
[src:16th-street-mall/16th-street-mall] Pei & Partners in collaboration with the urban design and landscape architecture firm OLIN.
[src:16th-street-mall/16th-street-mall] Construction was funded by a US$75 million grant (equivalent to $293.1 million in 2025) from Federal Interstate Highway Transfer Funds and the Federal Urban Mass Transit Administration, with RTD providing a local match.
[src:16th-street-mall/16th-street-mall] The original 12+1⁄2-block, 4⁄5-mile (1.3 km) 16th Street Mall is considered a landmark of late-20th-century design, combining post–World War II Modernist geometry and lighting with Postmodern references to western motifs.
[src:16th-street-mall/16th-street-mall] Its granite paving—19-inch (48 cm) square blocks in charcoal gray, light gray, and "Colorado red"—forms a diamond pattern inspired by Navajo blankets and diamondback rattlesnake skin.
[src:16th-street-mall/16th-street-mall] Other unique elements include distinctive light standards, northern red oaks and honey locust trees in engineered root boxes, fiberglass street furniture, and metal signage.
[src:16th-street-mall/16th-street-mall] After two years of construction, the Mall opened on October 4, 1982, with a ceremony that drew more than 200,000 visitors downtown.
[src:16th-street-mall/16th-street-mall] The Mall initially ran from Market Street Station to Civic Center Station at Broadway.
[src:16th-street-mall/16th-street-mall] Consolidating shuttle service along the route removed about 870 daily bus trips from surrounding streets, by funneling express and regional commuter buses to the bus stations.
[src:16th-street-mall/16th-street-mall] The Federal Transit Administration classifies the mall as a "fixed guideway", enabling RTD to receive operating funds under the same formula as a rail line.
[src:16th-street-mall/16th-street-mall] In 1994, the addition of light rail service on California and Stout streets added a third transit hub to the mall.
[src:16th-street-mall/16th-street-mall] The improvements on the street were extended three block into Lower Downtown in 1994 reaching Wynkoop Street, which included the demolition of the 16th Street Viaduct.
[src:16th-street-mall/16th-street-mall] Four more blocks into the Central Platte Valley district were added in 2012 ending at Wewatta Street.
[src:16th-street-mall/16th-street-mall] These extensions feature wide sidewalks and streetscape upgrades but not the older Mall's granite paving, reaching a total length of 1+1⁄4-mile (2.0 km) and 18+1⁄2-blocks.
[src:16th-street-mall/16th-street-mall] However, the segment from Wewatta to Wynkoop Streets is partly open to local vehicle traffic.
[src:16th-street-mall/16th-street-mall] RTD purchased Union Station in 2001 and started the process of redeveloping the historic station along with 19.85 acres (8.03 ha) of land in LoDo, to create a new transit hub that would replace Market Street Station.
[src:16th-street-mall/16th-street-mall] To enable the project, the Free MallRide was extended west from Market Street to Wynkoop Street that year and to Union Station in 2002, coinciding with the opening of a new light rail spur.
[src:16th-street-mall/16th-street-mall] In 2014, RTD opened an underground bus concourse at Union Station and closed Market Street Station.
[src:16th-street-mall/16th-street-mall] The land was sold to a developer for $11 million, which helped fund the redevelopment of Union Station, and the station site was transformed into a mixed-use building with residential, office, retail and restaurant space.
[src:16th-street-mall/16th-street-mall] By the 2010s, the granite paving was showing significant deterioration, prompting multiple studies calling for comprehensive reconstruction.
[src:16th-street-mall/16th-street-mall] In April 2022, work began on a $149 million rebuild, with a planned completion date of fall 2025.
[src:16th-street-mall/16th-street-mall] Of the 199 honey locust trees and 83 northern red oaks of the original mall, only 143 locusts were still alive and the majority of the oaks had died by 2023.
[src:16th-street-mall/16th-street-mall] The remaining trees were nearing the end of their lifespan and removed and replanted with new honey locusts as well as overcup oaks, swamp white oaks, Kentucky coffeetrees, 'Morton' elms, and 'Morton' Miyabe maples.
[src:16th-street-mall/16th-street-mall] The renovation project concluded in 2025 with a cerebration of the reopening on October 4.
[src:16th-street-mall/16th-street-mall] With the end of the project it was officially renamed as simply 16th Street, dropping mall from the name of the pedestrian portion of the street.
[src:16th-street-mall/16th-street-mall] The 16th Street FreeRide is a free shuttle bus service operated by the RTD along the length of the 16th Street Mall, with buses stopping at every intersection.
[src:16th-street-mall/16th-street-mall] The service began in 1982 as the 16th Street MallRide, originally running between Market Street Station and Civic Center Station (16th & Broadway), two major RTD bus hubs at either end of downtown.
[src:16th-street-mall/16th-street-mall] In 1994, light rail transit service was added at 16th & California and 16th & Stout stations, creating a third transit hub along the mall.
[src:16th-street-mall/16th-street-mall] In 2011, the route was extended north of the mall on 16th Street to Denver Union Station.
[src:16th-street-mall/16th-street-mall] In 2014, Market Street Station was closed and replaced by the Union Station Transit Center.
[src:16th-street-mall/16th-street-mall] In 2025, coinciding with the dropping of "Mall" from the 16th Street Mall name, the service was renamed 16th Street FreeRide.
[src:16th-street-mall/16th-street-mall] As of 2024, the route provides connections between the A Line, B Line, E Line, G Line, N Line, and W Line and the bus hub at Denver Union Station; the D Line, H Line, and L Line at 16th & California and 16th & Stout stations; and the bus hub at Civic Center Station.
[src:16th-street-mall/16th-street-mall] In 2018, the route saw an average weekday ridership of 43,971, making it the busiest operated by RTD.
[src:16th-street-mall/16th-street-mall] Buses operate from 5:30 a.m. to midnight on weekdays, with slightly shorter service hours on weekends and holidays.
[src:16th-street-mall/16th-street-mall] During peak periods, shuttles can run as frequently as every 90 seconds, with service reduced to every 10 minutes in the early morning and late evening.
[src:16th-street-mall/16th-street-mall] Since the service's inception, RTD has used custom-designed right-hand drive buses.
[src:16th-street-mall/16th-street-mall] This configuration gives operators improved visibility of passengers boarding and alighting from the curb side, as well as pedestrians who often move close to the buses, which travel at speeds up to 12 miles per hour (19 km/h) in the open mall setting.
[src:16th-street-mall/16th-street-mall] The buses also feature a low-floor design with an open interior with minimal seating (currently 18 seats, out of a capacity of 106), and three doors, enabling near-level boarding and accommodating fast passenger flow both inside the bus and during boarding and alighting.
[src:16th-street-mall/16th-street-mall] The first-generation buses, used from 1982 to 1999, were diesel-powered and front-wheel drive.
[src:16th-street-mall/16th-street-mall] The second-generation "EcoMark" buses, used from 1999 to 2016, were series hybrids with wheel hub motors powered by batteries charged from a 70 horsepower (52 kW), 1.6-liter compressed natural gas engine supplied by Ford.
[src:16th-street-mall/16th-street-mall] The third-generation BYD K10MR buses, introduced in 2016, are fully battery electric.
[src:16th-street-mall/16th-street-mall] The Project for Public Spaces says of the Mall that it "provides the entire downtown with shuttle bus circulation and high quality pedestrian access to Union Station.
[src:16th-street-mall/a-line-rtd] The **A Line** (formerly the **University of Colorado A Line** for sponsorship reasons) is a Regional Transportation District (RTD) commuter rail line serving Denver and Aurora, Colorado, operating between downtown Denver and Denver International Airport (DIA).
[src:16th-street-mall/a-line-rtd] During planning and construction, it was also known as the **East Rail Line**, but most locals refer to it as the A Line.
[src:16th-street-mall/a-line-rtd] Despite its former title, the line does not serve the campuses of the University of Colorado.
[src:16th-street-mall/a-line-rtd] Mass transit has been under consideration for the corridor between Downtown Denver and Denver International Airport since the latter was proposed in the 1980s.
[src:16th-street-mall/a-line-rtd] The project gathered momentum in 1997 when a Major Investment Study was completed for the corridor, encouraging fixed-guideway mass transit (light rail or commuter rail), highway widening and general improvements.
[src:16th-street-mall/a-line-rtd] The project was approved as part of the FasTracks transit expansion package in November 2004, went through regulatory processes and was approved by the Federal Transit Administration in November 2009.
[src:16th-street-mall/a-line-rtd] In July 2007, it was decided to use electric instead of diesel propulsion over speed and air pollution concerns.
[src:16th-street-mall/a-line-rtd] RTD designated the line with the letter "A", denoting service to the **a**irport and **A**urora.
[src:16th-street-mall/a-line-rtd] Groundbreaking for the A Line was held on August 26, 2010.
[src:16th-street-mall/a-line-rtd] As the second line of RTD's FasTracks expansion plan, the East Corridor was constructed and operated under the Eagle P3 public–private partnership.
[src:16th-street-mall/a-line-rtd] The first electric multiple unit railcars were pulled along the route on April 3, 2015, commencing testing and commissioning of the line.
[src:16th-street-mall/a-line-rtd] Revenue service began on April 22, 2016.
[src:16th-street-mall/a-line-rtd] From the A line's opening in April 2016 and until mid-2018, there have been operational issues with the crossing gates due to software problems, resulting in frequent delays.
[src:16th-street-mall/a-line-rtd] Crossing arms have been coming down too early and staying down for too long, and did not react dynamically to variance in arrival and departing times.
[src:16th-street-mall/a-line-rtd] *Westword* listed the project on its 2016 Colorado Hall of Shame.
[src:16th-street-mall/a-line-rtd] The A Line shares crossings with Union Pacific tracks, adding to the complexity to the crossing gates.
[src:16th-street-mall/a-line-rtd] In June 2018, the FRA approved a plan to remove the flaggers monitoring the crossing gates along the A Line.
[src:16th-street-mall/a-line-rtd] This approval also allows local jurisdictions to submit requests to the FRA to establish "quiet zones", removing the need for trains crossing through the gates to blow their horns.
[src:16th-street-mall/a-line-rtd] As of February 2019, approval for "quiet zones" at nine of the line's crossings has been granted, to be in effect on March 1, 2019; see Normal Whistle Codes.
[src:16th-street-mall/a-line-rtd] The A Line route follows and remains within a mile of Interstate 25, Interstate 70, and the airport access highway (Peña Boulevard).
[src:16th-street-mall/a-line-rtd] The line makes use of a preexisting Union Pacific Railroad right-of-way along the portion of the route from downtown Denver heading east, then deviates to the north along Peña Boulevard in a newly created right-of-way.
[src:16th-street-mall/a-line-rtd] Peña Boulevard was designed with an extra-wide median between its inbound and outbound lanes that could have been used for rail transit, though ultimately the East Rail Corridor alignment was offset from the highway right-of-way.
[src:16th-street-mall/a-line-rtd] Leaving Union Station the line follows the Union Pacific corridor past Coors Field to reach a station at 38th and Blake Streets shared with the future Central Corridor expansion.
[src:16th-street-mall/a-line-rtd] From there the line turns east alongside 40th Avenue past the Denver Union Pacific Intermodal Yard.
[src:16th-street-mall/a-line-rtd] Just east of Josephine Street the corridor turns two blocks north then east again to stay along the Union Pacific corridor to reach the 40th Avenue and Colorado Boulevard station.
[src:16th-street-mall/a-line-rtd] After passing under Colorado Boulevard the line parallels Smith Road, with a station at Central Park Boulevard in the redevelopment area of the decommissioned Stapleton International Airport.
[src:16th-street-mall/a-line-rtd] Shortly after entering Aurora, the line reaches Peoria station, which is shared with the R Line.
[src:16th-street-mall/a-line-rtd] Continuing east, alongside Smith Road, the line passes under Peoria Street and then Interstate 225.
[src:16th-street-mall/a-line-rtd] Just west of Airport Boulevard, the line rises on a viaduct curving north over the Union Pacific tracks, Airport Boulevard, 32nd Avenue, and Interstate 70.
[src:16th-street-mall/a-line-rtd] Having left the Union Pacific corridor, the viaduct then descends to a station at the existing Park and Ride at 40th Avenue and Airport Boulevard.
[src:16th-street-mall/a-line-rtd] From there the line reenters Denver, following the east side of Peña Boulevard.
[src:16th-street-mall/a-line-rtd] North of 56th Avenue it enters an added to the line construction Peña Boulevard station at 61st Avenue.
[src:16th-street-mall/a-line-rtd] The line continues north and east, parallel to Peña Boulevard and crossing over E-470.
[src:16th-street-mall/a-line-rtd] Turning north, the line crosses over Peña Boulevard adjacent to DIA runway 7/25 and then runs east between the airport secure area and 78th Avenue.
[src:16th-street-mall/a-line-rtd] The line then crosses over the south/west terminal exit lanes of Peña Boulevard ending at a station on the south side of the DIA Hotel and Transit Center, itself at the south end of the DIA Jeppesen Terminal.
[src:16th-street-mall/accolade-elm-hybrid] The parent tree at the Morton Arboretum is noted for the resemblance of its habit to the American elm *Ulmus americana*, its upright-arching branches creating the familiar vase-shape, although the tree does not grow as large as the iconic native elm, reaching scarcely 20 m at maturity.
[src:16th-street-mall/accolade-elm-hybrid] Its glossy, deep green leaves are also markedly smaller, rarely exceeding 8 cm in length.
[src:16th-street-mall/accolade-elm-hybrid] The tree is commercially propagated by grafting onto an *Ulmus pumila* rootstock.
[src:16th-street-mall/accolade-elm-hybrid] Accolade has a propensity to produce co-dominant stems and major branches with bark inclusions, demanding corrective pruning on at least an annual basis where planted in towns.
[src:16th-street-mall/accolade-elm-hybrid] In its 90+ years, the original tree at Morton has survived three epidemics of Dutch elm disease there unscathed.
[src:16th-street-mall/accolade-elm-hybrid] However, two trees included in trials at the University of Minnesota were found to be afflicted by the disease in 2004, although one appears to have recovered completely.
[src:16th-street-mall/accolade-elm-hybrid] The cultivar has also proved to be highly resistant to elm yellows and the elm leaf beetle *Xanthogaleruca luteola* , but not to the Japanese beetle, which can cause extensive foliar damage.
[src:16th-street-mall/accolade-elm-hybrid] Accolade is reputed to grow well in almost all soils save those excessively wet, and is notably drought-tolerant and cold hardy.
[src:16th-street-mall/accolade-elm-hybrid] In artificial freezing tests at the Morton Arboretum the LT50 (temp. at which 50% of tissues die) was found to be −35.5 °C.
[src:16th-street-mall/accolade-elm-hybrid] The tree grows vigorously at first, gaining as much as one metre per annum, but slows to approximately half that rate with maturity.
[src:16th-street-mall/accolade-elm-hybrid] Thus, a typical 20-year-old tree could be expected to have reached 14 m in height with a crown about 5 m in width.
[src:16th-street-mall/accolade-elm-hybrid] Trees grown by Tollgate Education, Michigan State University, at Novi were the most vigorous and robust of the 37 different cultivars and species under assessment, described as looking like 'men among boys'.
[src:16th-street-mall/accolade-elm-hybrid] Accolade is being evaluated in the National Elm Trial coordinated by Colorado State University.
[src:16th-street-mall/accolade-elm-hybrid] Accolade was introduced to Europe in 2006 and is now in commerce in the Netherlands.
[src:16th-street-mall/accolade-elm-hybrid] Accolade was crossed with the hybrid cultivar 'Morton Plainsman' = Vanguard.
[src:16th-street-mall/accolade-elm-hybrid] A selection of the resultant seedlings was marketed under the name 'Charisma', later changed to 'Morton Glossy' = Triumph.
[src:16th-street-mall/acer-miyabei] It is a small to medium-sized deciduous tree growing to 10–20 m (33–66 ft) tall, with a trunk 30–40 cm (12–16 in) diameter with rough, grey-brown bark.
[src:16th-street-mall/acer-miyabei] The leaves are five-lobed (the basal pair of lobes usually small), 7–20 cm (3–8 in) long and 12–20 cm (5–8 in) broad, with a 5–15 cm (2–6 in) long petiole; the petiole bleeds white latex if cut.
[src:16th-street-mall/acer-miyabei] The flowers are produced in spring at the same time as the leaves open, yellow-green, in erect corymbs.
[src:16th-street-mall/acer-miyabei] The fruit is a samara with two winged seeds aligned at 180°, each seed 8 mm (0.31 in) wide, flat, with a 2 cm (0.79 in) wing.
[src:16th-street-mall/acer-miyabei] It is an endangered species, confined to scattered locations close to streams and rivers.
[src:16th-street-mall/acer-miyabei] It is closely related to *Acer miaotaiense* from China—some authors treat this as a subspecies of *A. miyabei*, as *Acer miyabei* subsp.
[src:16th-street-mall/acer-miyabei] *miaotaiense* (P.C.Tsoong) E.Murray—and to *Acer campestre* from Europe.
[src:16th-street-mall/acer-miyabei] This tree is cultivated as an ornamental plant in the United States, but is not common in trade.
[src:16th-street-mall/acer-miyabei] It withstands cold temperatures, urban conditions, and drought once established.
[src:16th-street-mall/acer-miyabei] It is a non-invasive substitute for *Acer platanoides*.
[src:16th-street-mall/acer-miyabei] A dense, uniform cultivar has been selected at the Morton Arboretum named *Acer miyabei* 'Morton' and marketed under the trade name State Street® maple.
[src:16th-street-mall/adventhealth-porter] On February 16, 1930, Porter Sanitarium Hospital opened with 100 beds.
[src:16th-street-mall/adventhealth-porter] Porter who was inspired to give $1 million and 40 acres (16 ha) to the Seventh-day Adventist Church after being treated at two sanatoriums owned by the Seventh-day Adventist Church.
[src:16th-street-mall/adventhealth-porter] In 1996, Porter Adventist Hospital became part of the joint venture Centura Health when it was founded by PorterCare Adventist Health System and Catholic Health Initiatives.
[src:16th-street-mall/adventhealth-porter] In late June 2000, PorterCare Adventist Health System and Adventist Health System/Sunbelt reached a $10 million agreement.
[src:16th-street-mall/adventhealth-porter] It would allow Adventist Health System to acquire the 30 percent of Centura Health owned by PorterCare Adventist Health System.
[src:16th-street-mall/adventhealth-porter] On October 1, 2001, PorterCare Adventist Health System merged with Adventist Health System Sunbelt Healthcare Corporation after approval from the Federal Trade Commission.
[src:16th-street-mall/adventhealth-porter] In late 2017, the Colorado Senate passed a law requiring hospitals to have their chargemaster on its website by January 1, 2018.
[src:16th-street-mall/adventhealth-porter] The Centers for Medicare & Medicaid Services also required all hospitals to do the same by January 1, 2021.
[src:16th-street-mall/adventhealth-porter] On August 9, 2022, Porter Adventist Hospital still had refused to comply.
[src:16th-street-mall/adventhealth-porter] To force hospitals to comply the Colorado House of Representatives and Colorado Senate both passed laws forbidding hospitals from collecting debt by reporting patients to collection agencies.
[src:16th-street-mall/adventhealth-porter] On February 14, 2023, Centura Health announced that it would split up.
[src:16th-street-mall/adventhealth-porter] On August 1, Centura Health split up with Porter Adventist Hospital rebranding to AdventHealth Porter.
[src:16th-street-mall/adventhealth-porter] On October 30, AdventHealth Porter closed when it lost heat and hot water at 8:45 a.m. after their second boiler failed during a cold snap.
[src:16th-street-mall/adventhealth-porter] Two weeks before, the hospital had its first boiler fail and they ordered a replacement from a company in Texas.
[src:16th-street-mall/adventhealth-porter] 90 patients were transferred to AdventHealth Castle Rock, AdventHealth Littleton and AdventHealth Parker by South Metro Fire Rescue and local EMS.
[src:16th-street-mall/adventhealth-porter] On October 31, 55 patients were transferred and 30 others were released.
[src:16th-street-mall/adventhealth-porter] Its two boilers were fixed and a temporary one was installed on November 1.
[src:16th-street-mall/adventhealth-porter] AdventHealth Porter reopened resuming its emergency and acute care services.
[src:16th-street-mall/adventhealth-porter] On February 21, 2018, the Colorado Department of Public Health and Environment was told of a sterilization breach at Porter Adventist Hospital.
[src:16th-street-mall/adventhealth-porter] The following day they did a survey of the infection control practices at the hospital.
[src:16th-street-mall/adventhealth-porter] The Joint Commission visited the hospital in February after hearing complaints at the hospital.
[src:16th-street-mall/adventhealth-porter] On April 3, the Colorado Department of Public Health and Environment did a second survey after hearing about inadequately cleaned surgical equipment.
[src:16th-street-mall/adventhealth-porter] On April 4, the Colorado Department of Public Health and Environment announced to the public that at Porter Adventist Hospital they were investigating a sterilization breach.
[src:16th-street-mall/adventhealth-porter] On the same day as the announcement the hospital mailed 5,800 letters to patients who were put at risk from July 21, 2016, to February 20, 2018.
[src:16th-street-mall/adventhealth-porter] During that time period patients who had orthopedic surgery were put at risk of Hepatitis B, Hepatitis C and HIV.
[src:16th-street-mall/adventhealth-porter] During its investigation the Colorado Department of Public Health and Environment found out that the hospital knew that patients were getting infections as early as 2017.
[src:16th-street-mall/adventhealth-porter] On April 5, Porter Adventist Hospital canceled almost all of its surgeries.
[src:16th-street-mall/adventhealth-porter] On April 6, the hospital offered patients testing for blood diseases.
[src:16th-street-mall/adventhealth-porter] On the same day Porter Adventist Hospital suspended all surgeries until the Colorado Department of Public Health and Environment considered it safe to reopen all operating rooms.
[src:16th-street-mall/adventhealth-porter] On April 11, the Colorado Department of Public Health and Environment found some patients had surgical site infections.
[src:16th-street-mall/adventhealth-porter] The next day Porter Adventist Hospital resumed some of its surgeries.
[src:16th-street-mall/adventhealth-porter] On June 15, Porter Adventist Hospital was sued by 67 former patients and 20 spouses.
[src:16th-street-mall/adventhealth-porter] Those suing the hospital later increased to over 200 and then to over 3,000.
[src:16th-street-mall/adventhealth-porter] They claim that the contaminated surgical instruments were also used for other surgeries, with hundreds of them getting sick from hepatitis B, meningitis, urinary tract infections, E. coli and staph infections.
[src:16th-street-mall/adventhealth-porter] One patient died from sepsis and pneumonia after having surgery at the hospital.
[src:16th-street-mall/adventhealth-porter] Before the plaintiffs sued they used the Colorado Open Records Act to request the release of the documents of the Colorado Department of Public Health and Environments investigation.
[src:16th-street-mall/adventhealth-porter] After the documents were released Porter Adventist Hospital asked a judge to ban the use of some of the documents, even to order them to be destroyed or returned.
[src:16th-street-mall/adventhealth-porter] The Colorado Attorney General also agreed that the documents should have never been released and ordered them destroyed, which the plaintiffs refused to do.
[src:16th-street-mall/adventhealth-porter] In July 2020, Denver District Court Judge Morris B.
[src:16th-street-mall/adventhealth-porter] Hoffman rejected all of the protective orders requested by Porter Adventist Hospital, which it had requested in May of that year.
[src:16th-street-mall/adventhealth-porter] Porter Adventist Hospital appealed the ruling to the Colorado Supreme Court.
[src:16th-street-mall/adventhealth-porter] On January 13, 2021, the judges heard the appeal and were reluctant to overturn the decision of the district court judge.
[src:16th-street-mall/adventhealth-porter] In the end the judges dismissed the appeal and returned the case back to Denver District Court Judge Morris B.
[src:16th-street-mall/adventhealth-porter] On June 21, 2023, the Denver District Court Judge accepted the $6.5 million class action settlement.
[src:16th-street-mall/adventhealth-porter] On July 3, 2018, Porter Adventist Hospital announced that it would suspend its kidney, liver and pancreas organ transplantation program to make improvements with the help of the Florida Hospital Transplant Institute.
[src:16th-street-mall/adventhealth-porter] This affected 232 patients who received letters telling them that they would have to go to other Presbyterian/St.
[src:16th-street-mall/adventhealth-porter] Luke's Medical Center and UCHealth hospitals for their procedures.
[src:16th-street-mall/adventhealth-porter] On July 19, 2019, Porter Adventist Hospital announced that it would resume its organ transplantation program.
[src:16th-street-mall/adventhealth-porter] On October 25, 2023, AdventHealth Porter signed a commercial agreement with Aclarion to bring their Nociscan technology to Denver.
[src:16th-street-mall/adventhealth-porter] The hospital will become the first health facility in the city to use the technology, to treat patients with chronic low back pain.
[src:16th-street-mall/adventhealth-porter] In February 2026, the hospital began offering the **Voucher Program** from the National Kidney Registry, it allows donors to give a kidney to family members years in advance.
[src:16th-street-mall/adventhealth-porter] The hospital received a grade A from The Leapfrog Group from June 2012 to April 2018, and again from May 2022 to May 2026.
[src:16th-street-mall/adventhealth-porter] AdventHealth Porter received from the Centers for Medicare & Medicaid Services a five-star rating from 2023 to 2024.
[src:16th-street-mall/alamo-placita-denver] The district is bounded by Downing Street (east), Speer Boulevard (south), Pennsylvania Street (west), 6th Avenue (north) west of Clarkson Street and 7th Avenue (north) east of Clarkson Street.
[src:16th-street-mall/alamo-placita-denver] Alamo Placita is part of a larger official neighborhood called Speer.
[src:16th-street-mall/alamo-placita-denver] The history of the Alamo Placita Historic District tells the story of 1860s prairie land along Cherry Creek just three miles (5 km) southeast of the new town of Denver.
[src:16th-street-mall/alamo-placita-denver] Farsighted investor Moses Hallett, an attorney from Illinois, bought the land in 1864.
[src:16th-street-mall/alamo-placita-denver] Hallett’s quarter section of land became Arlington Park Addition, and later, Alamo Placita neighborhood.
[src:16th-street-mall/alamo-placita-denver] By 1887, Denver’s southern city limit was the northern border of Hallett’s claim (now East 6th Avenue).
[src:16th-street-mall/alamo-placita-denver] A road on the eastern edge of Hallett’s land, called Hallett Road, is now Downing Street.
[src:16th-street-mall/alamo-placita-denver] In 1889, Hallett sold his land to the Arlington Park Land and Improvement Company and became one of several investors in the company.
[src:16th-street-mall/alamo-placita-denver] Speer came to the West in 1878 seeking a cure for his tuberculosis.
[src:16th-street-mall/alamo-placita-denver] He recovered and exhibited boundless energy that defied any earlier malaise.
[src:16th-street-mall/alamo-placita-denver] Speer is remembered for becoming Denver’s first mayor under home rule in 1904, his three terms as mayor, his exuberance for Denver’s City Beautiful Movement, his support for the Denver park system, his boss-style politics, and his personal gains from real estate investments.
[src:16th-street-mall/alamo-placita-denver] Much less well known were Speer’s important connections with the Alamo Placita neighborhood.
[src:16th-street-mall/alamo-placita-denver] Those connections included, first, the fact that Alamo Placita neighborhood was Speer’s first major real estate investment.
[src:16th-street-mall/alamo-placita-denver] He formed a syndicate to develop the land.
[src:16th-street-mall/alamo-placita-denver] When Arlington Park Addition was created, it became the first client for Speer’s newly formed real estate company.
[src:16th-street-mall/alamo-placita-denver] Second, Speer’s creation of an addition and then an amusement park provided him with experience as the central figure in pulling big plans together with powerful Denver men.
[src:16th-street-mall/alamo-placita-denver] Robert and Kate Speer built their residence at 505 Clarkson Street (now demolished) in 1890, and they lived there until 1906.
[src:16th-street-mall/alamo-placita-denver] The grand opening for Arlington Park was held on the Fourth of July 1892.
[src:16th-street-mall/alamo-placita-denver] An extravagant theatrical production, “The Last Days of Pompeii,” was the main attraction, involving 300 actors and a 54-foothigh set of Mt.
[src:16th-street-mall/alamo-placita-denver] Vesuvius erupted, a large fireworks display accompanied the eruption.
[src:16th-street-mall/alamo-placita-denver] In true Speer style, the grandeur was heavily promoted and an estimated 12,000 people attended.
[src:16th-street-mall/alamo-placita-denver] The future of Arlington Park looked bright, and surely more events were anticipated.
[src:16th-street-mall/alamo-placita-denver] Anticipation disappeared when the 1893 Silver Crash brought the economy to a standstill.
[src:16th-street-mall/alamo-placita-denver] In 1898, Arlington Park reopened under the name Chutes Park.
[src:16th-street-mall/alamo-placita-denver] The new feature was “the chutes,” a graded waterfall that took riders in boats down into the lake at the bottom.
[src:16th-street-mall/alamo-placita-denver] Two new attractions in May 1899 lured fun seekers.
[src:16th-street-mall/alamo-placita-denver] Miss Sadie Boynton, recently of Paris, France, would thrill all by “shooting the chutes” on a bicycle.
[src:16th-street-mall/alamo-placita-denver] Also, “Professor Barnes’ muchheralded herd of driving and diving elks” would march up a ramp and plunge, one at a time, off a 60-foot (18 m)-high platform into a tank of water.
[src:16th-street-mall/alamo-placita-denver] Fires in 1901 and 1902 closed the amusement park forever, pleasing nearby neighbors who found living near the facility quite trying.
[src:16th-street-mall/alamo-placita-denver] The 1889 Arlington Park Addition was the first and largest subdivision platted on Moses Hallett’s land.
[src:16th-street-mall/alamo-placita-denver] Essentially, it included almost all of the land that was not part of the amusement park.
[src:16th-street-mall/alamo-placita-denver] 6th Avenue to approximately one-half block south of E.
[src:16th-street-mall/alamo-placita-denver] 4th Avenue, and from Logan Street to the alley between Corona and Downing Streets.
[src:16th-street-mall/alamo-placita-denver] Speer and Company began accepting deposits on the property.
[src:16th-street-mall/alamo-placita-denver] By the end of February, 319 lots had sold for $217,000.
[src:16th-street-mall/alamo-placita-denver] Speer’s smiling face is more smiling than ever.” Notable early investors were Colonel John Arkins, owner of the Rocky Mountain News; John Cochran, the city postmaster; and T.M.
[src:16th-street-mall/alamo-placita-denver] Patterson, the first Democratic congressman from the State of Colorado.
[src:16th-street-mall/alamo-placita-denver] The vigorous rate of growth in the Arlington Park Addition stopped in 1893.
[src:16th-street-mall/alamo-placita-denver] Building permits were lost for the years 1893 to 1900, but evidence points to a gradual recovery in Arlington Park home building.
[src:16th-street-mall/alamo-placita-denver] The new homes tended to be more modest than grand, and the new residents tended to be less well-known citizens.
[src:16th-street-mall/alamo-placita-denver] The neighborhood was serving as an affordable destination for new renters and first-time home-owners— particularly first-and second-generation European immigrants.
[src:16th-street-mall/alamo-placita-denver] Two groups of immigrants were especially predominant in Arlington Park.
[src:16th-street-mall/alamo-placita-denver] Scandinavian immigrants, primarily Swedish, were to make Hallett’s land their home in their new country.
[src:16th-street-mall/alamo-placita-denver] And later, Greeks would follow the path of the Swedes.
[src:16th-street-mall/alamo-placita-denver] Half of Colorado’s Swedes lived in the Denver area in 1890.
[src:16th-street-mall/alamo-placita-denver] At first the Swedish residents of Alamo Placita were primarily involved in the building trades, domestic service, and gardening, and quite a few Alamo Placita homes were constructed by Swedish craftsmen.
[src:16th-street-mall/alamo-placita-denver] Soon, however, the Swedish-Americans began to embrace a variety of occupations.
[src:16th-street-mall/alamo-placita-denver] By the early 1930s, Alamo Placita gained significant numbers of Greek-Americans.
[src:16th-street-mall/alamo-placita-denver] Most were moving from the environs of their church north of Capitol Hill at E.
[src:16th-street-mall/alamo-placita-denver] 37th Avenue and Lafayette Street, the location of the first Greek Orthodox Church in Denver.
[src:16th-street-mall/alamo-placita-denver] In 1933, the Greek Orthodox Church moved to 574 Pennsylvania Street.
[src:16th-street-mall/alamo-placita-denver] A residence on the Pennsylvania Street site was demolished and the Greeks built a new Assumption Greek Orthodox Church.
[src:16th-street-mall/alamo-placita-denver] The church was designed with the traditional onion-shaped domes associated with Eastern Orthodoxy.
[src:16th-street-mall/alamo-placita-denver] The presence of this building brought a rich, new, visible ethnic identity to Alamo Placita.
[src:16th-street-mall/alamo-placita-denver] This church was the central Greek church of Colorado.
[src:16th-street-mall/alamo-placita-denver] In 1973, the church moved to a spectacular new Assumption Greek Orthodox Church on E.
[src:16th-street-mall/alamo-placita-denver] With the building boom of the post-World War II years taking newer populations to the city fringe or new suburban communities, most of the Alamo Placita neighborhood continued to draw those who needed more affordable housing.
[src:16th-street-mall/alamo-placita-denver] Some developers demolished a few early residences to build more lucrative, multifamily apartments.
[src:16th-street-mall/alamo-placita-denver] Most of these new apartments were built on a relatively small scale.
[src:16th-street-mall/alamo-placita-denver] According to Assessor records, by 1930 approximately 90 percent of the present Alamo Placita Historic District buildings were built; by 1940, 94 percent were built.
[src:16th-street-mall/alamo-placita-denver] These include single-family dwellings, multifamily dwellings, and the few commercial buildings in the district.
[src:16th-street-mall/alamo-placita-denver] Neighborhood development continued with change occurring at a very slow pace, reacting to the ups and downs of the economy.
[src:16th-street-mall/alamo-placita-denver] During the 1960s, 1970s, and 1980s, the value of the neighborhood as a family-oriented environment close to the heart of the city was quietly rediscovered by young professionals and others.
[src:16th-street-mall/alamo-placita-denver] Lawyers, doctors, teachers, and businesspeople were moving into Alamo Placita in greater numbers, joining trade craftsmen, clerks, salesmen, and others.
[src:16th-street-mall/alamo-placita-denver] An example of one such couple is Richard and Dottie Lamm, who lived at 531 Emerson Street in the 1960s, before Lamm became a three-term governor of Colorado.
[src:16th-street-mall/alamo-placita-denver] The rediscovery of the neighborhood included an appreciation and respect for its architecture.
[src:16th-street-mall/alamo-placita-denver] Growing numbers of residents became aware of the neighborhood’s architectural integrity.
[src:16th-street-mall/alamo-placita-denver] Their interest led to a desire to protect their environment and learn more about neighborhood history.
[src:16th-street-mall/alamo-placita-denver] This in turn formed the foundation for the creation of Alamo Placita Neighbors Association.
[src:16th-street-mall/alamo-placita-denver] Alamo Placita Historic District has some homes built for some early prominent Denverites, but mainly recognizes the 1889 to 1942 environment of middle-income building trades and professional people, along with early clerks, Tramway workers, railroad men, and the like.
[src:16th-street-mall/alamo-placita-denver] The first district residents expressed their aspirations for success in part through building their neighborhood in important architectural styles of the day.
[src:16th-street-mall/alamo-placita-denver] Investors who built single- and multifamily residences followed this lead.
[src:16th-street-mall/alamo-placita-denver] Together they created an environment of lower-scale dwellings with streetscapes that respected visually pleasing setbacks accommodating gardens, lawns, and sidewalks.
[src:16th-street-mall/alamo-placita-denver] The gentle intermingling of architectural styles, building materials, and individual decoration remains clearly apparent despite more recent setback violations where a few demolished original structures have been replaced.
[src:16th-street-mall/alamo-placita-denver] Though the scale of a few newer buildings is too large, only one of the newer noncontributing structures is in serious height violation at 12 stories.
[src:16th-street-mall/alamo-placita-denver] The earliest district residences were designed in Victorian-era styles.
[src:16th-street-mall/alamo-placita-denver] After 1893, when the Victorian-era influence began to wane, much of the district remained undeveloped.
[src:16th-street-mall/alamo-placita-denver] Alamo Placita residents were quicker than wealthier citizens to embrace the Arts and Crafts Movement, interpreted mainly in Alamo Placita through Foursquares and Bungalows.
[src:16th-street-mall/alamo-placita-denver] Wealthier citizens tended to express their status through the Classical Revival-style architecture of their residences.
[src:16th-street-mall/alamo-placita-denver] Less wealthy citizens were more open to the perceived practicality of new designs.
[src:16th-street-mall/alamo-placita-denver] Over time, in tandem with the Arts and Crafts influence, came a sprinkling of the popular Tudor-style dwellings, Spanish Mission-style dwellings, and others that spoke to Denver’s tenuous southwestern U.S. identity.
[src:16th-street-mall/alamo-placita-denver] The physical context of the district includes the small commercial buildings that were built along district borders, E.
[src:16th-street-mall/alamo-placita-denver] 6th Avenue, Speer Boulevard, and Downing Street.
[src:16th-street-mall/alamo-placita-denver] In 2000, the Denver Landmark Preservation Commission unanimously recommended designation of the Alamo Placita Historic District based on the significance of its history, architecture, and geography.
[src:16th-street-mall/alamo-placita-denver] The City Council agreed, unanimously voting to approve the designation on June 12, 2000.
[src:16th-street-mall/alamo-placita-denver] The Esquire Theatre at 590 Downing Street is the district's most prominent building, though because its 1965 exterior redesign by Richard L.
[src:16th-street-mall/alamo-placita-denver] Crowther falls outside the district's period of significance (1889-1942), it is classified as non-contributing.
